snippet.textDisplay:
Right im a big Star Wars fan i never went as far as signing that petition but i did greatly dislike The Last Jedi and i gotta say im getting tired of hearing all this talk of The Rise of Skywalker undoing the very things The Last Jedi was exploring. TLJ itself undid practically EVERYTHING The Force Awakens set up, but no one cared about that (atleast none of the casuals and non fans)!


This was what many of us big, hardcore fans hated about TLJ, how it was more of a deconstruction of the Star Wars mythos than anything else. I honestly believe the reason why many loved TLJ for "trying to do something different" is purely because these people were never big, passionate Star Wars fans, they were never invested in this franchise to begin with.


Kermode you're a great reviewer and critic and i honestly respect you, i just got to say here i pretty much fundamentally disagree with practically everything you have said here regarding this specific movie and to do with this issue of the Disney Trilogy.
Now us passionate fans seem to be being blamed for the reason why JJ. Abrams back-pedalled and chose to pander to us, YET WE NEVER EVEN WANTED THE SAME OLD THING ALL OVER AGAIN!!!!


We NEVER wanted the same ideas of a big, bad "Empire" using massive planet killing weapons to blow up planets! We NEVER wanted bigger "Death Stars", Tie Fighters and Storm Troopers all over again! We NEVER wanted that to begin with in Episode 7 TFA.


We wanted them to take things in new directions, new, original ideas for villains and threats, new, original and very "alien" looking planets, new ideas for how force sensitives can evolve with the force, and even maybe a further exploration into this "balance" of the force (that many get confused over); and we simply expected that the main protagonist Rey would have something to do with that.


Im just sick of the way all this has gone, people have us hardcore fans wrong, yeh we have a few picky sorts out there who dont want a "woman" main character or any new ideas introduced. But most of us were fine with Rey when she was introduced in TFA we found her interesting, and we just expected they would take it all somewhere, e.g. like ideas that Snoke could be a ancient threat that originated from Outside the Galaxy, thats original, thats a new idea.

snippet.textDisplay:
Rise of Skywalker has the unenviable position of ending a trilogy that should never have been started, was unfaithfully executed, and wasted its first film and much of its second. I didn't see it. I made the mistake of seeing The Last Jedi on the strength of Rogue One, which had given me false hope after the disaster that was The Force Awakens.


This entire trilogy is very much like Jurassic Park 3, the opening to which establishes Dr Grant and Dr Sattler as having separated, in order to justify Grant's position in the film. They undid what all the fans considered to be a closed and victorious storyline in order to justify the existence of the film, and then struggled to write a convincing story that wasn't just fan-service sequences. This trilogy does the same, in that it undoes Lucas's closed and victorious storyline of the Original and Prequel trilogies and essentially says "what if: no", spinning off a uninspired and lacklustre trilogy that didn't know what to do with itself. The Force Awakens was an almost exact replica of A New Hope; they just killed off the wisened mentor in the third act instead of the second. I left that film thinking "there are now seven Star Wars films and in THREE of them they blow up the Death Star". They tried so hard to fit absolutely ever aspect of A New Hope into The Force Awakens that they carved up the psyches of their own characters to do it. The rough, whooping boyishness of Han Solo was inserted into Finn's character, which meant that no sooner had he deserted the First Order, having seen his friends die in battle, he was whooping and hollering with glee while blowing them up. What a mess.


The entire point of the original trilogy is the story of Luke Skywalker. The entire point of the original six (i.e. prequels + originals) is the story of two Skywalkers who walk opposite paths and who meet up at the same point to bring balance to the Force. There's a fantastic essay out there called the Star Wars Ring Theory, which explains how the story of all six films is constructed in this brilliant circular structure and is supported by cinematographic choices between each pair of counterpart films. It couldn't be a more closed loop unless Lucas came out and said it in black and white. Undoing that loop to tell a story you haven't even figured out is the height of hubris and nothing short of mercenary.


There is one interesting point that you could use to branch the original six films into a new series, and that's the prophecy of "bringing balance to the Force". If you told a story about how the Jedi's interpretation of "balance" being "all Jedi, no Sith" was foolish, that would be a go-er. But undoing a victory to go an meander off into the nonsense this trilogy did is nothing better than fanfiction.

snippet.textDisplay: Beautifully put, couldn't agree more!  I'm glad people like you can voice an eloquent measured response into the world amongst a sea of people just yelling at each other, especially as my own feelings are quite a bit stronger, though in the same vein as yours.  The Rise of Skywalker felt totally spiteful towards The Last Jedi to an absurd, almost comical degree that stifled it from becoming something substantial in its own right, and that will always be such a shame and wasted opportunity.  The Force Awakens was very derivative but did a good job of reintroducing the world of Star Wars and getting people excited to see some promising new and interesting characters, but it absolutely needed The Last Jedi to instil some purpose, direction and soul to the trilogy that was uniquely its own that would've (if they'd leaned into it) achieved something transcendent by the end of episode 9.  Instead we got a cacophony of extraneous elements introduced at the series's 11th hour out of the blue and with nothing to set them up, coupled with spineless, cynical, market research-esque approach to try and appease a loud minority of self righteous internet brats who have no idea about the fundamentals of what makes for good story-telling, but preferred to see Luke do a bunch of back-flips and light sabre fighting and to crush star destroyers with his mind etc instead of go through some actual character development and challenges.  Such a colossal waste.

snippet.textDisplay: It looked terrific? Oh dear, Mark. If top of your list when commending this narrative mess is, "it looked terrific", then we're already scraping the bottom of the compliments barrel. It's Disney. Of course it's gonna look good. They've got billions to spend. But looks age; effects date, and all a movie ever has left are characters. That's why the OT is timeless, and why the sequel trilogy comes in for such flak. Normally you're a great champion of character-driven cinema, Mark. Which is why I'm agog at how you can justify the path taken by TLJ. Forget how it looked... It ignored the world-building, it ignored the in-universe rules, and it ignored the history of the characters. TROS was a fan fiction movie made out of desperation. Why? Because of the crimes and misdemeanour committed by Johnson. And it's sad. So very sad. No reason to talk about the plot? Would you have said the same about the OT? The prosecution rests.

snippet.textDisplay:
The Last Jedi was a terrible film with its numerous contrivances awkward comedy and meandering plot. Rain Johnson attempted to be clever by hitching his story to a philosophy of subverting expectations. In catering to that philosophy of subversion at every point, he manufactured a clunky, inorganic story.
What makes me upset is how film critics that I respect seemed to overlook all the clunky elements they would normally point out about other films and give this film high marks just for being different. Post modern storytelling can be refreshing if executed well. But TLJ failed in the execution.

snippet.textDisplay: I don’t agree with the vitriol but I also understand it. I actually can’t think of a reason to like the Last Jedi. Seriously, when people who like it explain why I’m still confused what they’re talking about. It was truly awful, and the worst thing I can think of saying about this trilogy is that it made me bored! It was boring! Trilogy 1 and trilogy 3, just awful films. Leave Star Wars alone now please.

snippet.textDisplay: Now we have all three films to look at, the decision to give TLJ to Rian Johnson seems more mental than it did when his attachment was announced. All three films by JJ would have led to a basically safe retread of the original trilogy, updated for a modern audience: fine. All three films by Rian Johnson would have led to a radical re-imagining of the whole shebang, and a chance to create something fresh out of a stock formula: also fine. Instead, TFA, while being a little too safe, built a house that TLJ gleefully set fire to, leaving TRoS to try to pick up the pieces; and so the audience who wanted something familiar, and the audience that wanted something different, were both left disappointed by the whole endeavour.
